Now Venus had been jealous at the virginity of Proserpine, Ceres’ daughter, and at her hidding Cupid shot the king of Shadows with his dart. lle then, beholding Proserpine, as she sported with her maidens in the vale of Enna, seized her, and bore her away in his chariot, driving his way through the fount of Cyane, who thereon was herself con- verted into water (341-437). Seeking her daughter in vain, by the light of torches kindled from AEtna, Ceres turned into a spotted lizard (stellio) the boy Stelles, who had mocked her eager thirst; and into a horned owl Ascalaphus, who testified to having seen Proserpine in Hades eat seven pomegranate-seeds whereby she was compelled to remain in her new abode.
